defaultCBM and Livelihoodsdefault&#xa0;
defaultCBM’s strategic framework for livelihood development stresses the importance of inclusive approache
defaults to skills development, access to financial services, and paid employment, with the underlying aim of enabling persons with disabilities to become productive contributors to social insurance systems. 
default&#xa0;
defaultCBM is working actively with the Centre for Financial
default Inclusion, an industry-facing think tank, at Accion (a global microfinance pioneer) on inclusive livelihood development and access to financial services. CBM is also in dialogue with the Village Savings and Loans organisation (VSL), with a view to includi
defaultng persons with disabilities. VSL is a pioneer in village savings and loans, and has nearly 
defaultnine
default million members, mostly in Africa.
default&#xa0;defaultIn recent years there has been marked growth in the number of persons with disabilities becoming involved in open employment, cooperatives, micro-finance and savings &amp; loans schemes. Last year, CBM skills development and work creation programmes reach over
default 100,000 people with disabilities. 
default&#xa0;
defaultParticipatory planning is used to involve the individual with a disability and his or her family, together with the economic realities of the community in which the individual lives, taking into account what products an
defaultd services are in high demand and short supply. 
default&#xa0;
defaultA twin-track approach of economic empowerment of persons with disabilities, together with sustained advocacy for inclusive livelihood development at local, national and international levels has been shown t
defaulto be a successful model of engagement.
default&#xa0;
defaultCase Study: Inclusive Development through Organic Farming default&#xa0;
default“Inclusive Development through Organic Farming” is a five
default-
defaultyear project
default and initiative of 
defaultCBM
default partner Naman
default Seva Samiti
default, with the aim of providing livelihood
default opportunities for a total of 1,500 farmers with disabilities and their families in Madhya Pradesh
default,
default central India. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThis is the first project in India which trains people with disabilities in organic farming in their local language. Participants in the pr
defaultogramme include people with physical, hearing and visual impairments as well as parents of children with disabilities. During the project, farmers will develop a cooperative movement where they are responsible for the entire production and marketing cycle.
default&#xa0;defaultEach year, 300-350 farmers receive training in soil testing, the production of organic manure, crop selection and processing of products through a mix of both theory lessons at the training centre and practical sessions in the fields. Farmers also take p
defaultart in exposure visits to learn from the experiences of other farmers’ 
defaultgroups and organisations in different parts of the country. In addition to training, Naman provides transportation, promotion and marketing support and reaches out to larger markets and
default suppliers of bigger supermarkets wherever feasible.
default&#xa0;
defaultNaman’s advocacy activities at government level in Madhya Pradesh have led to the state government providing technical support for the project and declaring Athner block as an ‘organic block’. 
defaultAlready,
default other 
defaultorganis
defaultations
default are approaching Naman to share its experiences and gain help in establishing 
defaultpilot projects
default 
defaultin other parts of India.
default              
default              
default              
default              
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultFarmer showing her organic vegetable productiondefault 
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultMost importantly, the project is bringing significant change 
defaultto the lives of persons with disabilities and their families. Pe
defaultrsons
default with disabilities are leading a process of economic empowerment and agricultural innovation, changing perceptions within the wider community, giving hope to thousands of persons with dis
defaultabilities in rural India. 
