default&#xa0;defaultCase Study: defaultA voice for mental health in Sierra Leonedefault&#xa0;
defaultIn Sierra Leone, mental health needs are especially great as 
defaulta result of the 1991-2002 civil war that left deep scars on the nation's psychological well-being and its social capital. 
defaultA whole generation of young people missed out on education, and continues
default to struggle to participate in the economy. 
defaultPeople with psychosocial disabilities in
default Sierra Leone are often ostracis
defaulted
default from their communities and human rights violations are common. This may be due to traditional beliefs that attribute mental illness to spiritual causes and often blame the person with the problem. A lack of public health awareness and negative attitudes s
defaulturrounding mental illness has contributed to high levels of stigma and discrimination.  
default&#xa0;
defaultExisting services consist of a single national psychiatric hospital, which has shortages of staff, medication, and other essential resources, resulting in 
defaultchallenging
default conditions
default, including routine chaining of patients. The few civil society services that started after the war are now closed. With no 
defaultdecentralized
default mental health services available through government health services, people must rely on traditional treatm
defaultent or travel to the hospital in 
defaultthe capital 
defaultFreetown.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Mental Health Coalition of Sierra Leonedefault&#xa0;defaultThe Mental Health Coalition of Sierra
default Leone was founded in September
default 2010
default with the purpose of creating a body that empowers stakeholders to advocate for t
defaultheir rights, promoting practical change that will improve quality of life and inclusion in society.
