defaultCBM and Disaster Preparednessdefault&#xa0;
defaultCBM knows that the involvement of pe
defaultrsons
default with disabilit
defaulties
default disaster management planning saves lives.  
defaultDisasters have a huge impact on human infrastructure, and livelihoods. The key 
defaultto
default diminishing their impact is to reduce people’s vulnerability. Through inclusive Disaster Risk Reduction (DRR) programmes, incorporated in human development plans and poverty 
defaultreduction programmes, risks can be reduced and communities’ resilience to disasters can be strengthened.
defaultPersons with disabilities are often overlooked throughout the disaster management cycle and especially during relief operations, and are seldom 
defaultconsidered as important actors in conflict prevention even though they are often more exposed during conflicts and displacement
default. The UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (CRPD), in its articles 11 and 32
default, requires that persons with di
defaultsabilities benefit from and participate in disaster relief, emergency response and disaster risk reduction strategies 
defaultas pe
defaultrsons
default with disabilit
defaulties
default are the most vulnerable in a disaster situation. The disaster preparedness and disaster risk reduction traini
defaultng run by CBM partners in 
defaultt
defaulthe Philippines before Typhoon Haiyan struck has shown how effective this can be through the number of lives saved.  
default&#xa0;
defaultCBM adheres to the 
defaultk
defaultey principles for inclusive disaster risk reduction policies which include:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;defaultCase Study: Putting Disability on the agenda of Disaster Risk Manadefaultgementdefault&#xa0;defaultThe Disability 
defaultI
defaultnclusive Disaster Risk Reduction Network for Asia and Pacific participated in the Global Platform for Disaster Risk Management in Geneva in May 2013. The network achieved its objective of assuring that disability is included and 
defaultmainstreamed across disaster risk reduction management projects 
defaultand working towards a disability
default-
defaultinclusive post Hyogo Framework for Action. For the first time disability was included in the outcome document. 
default“Even the best early warning systems and prepar
defaultedness efforts to evacuate populations in dangers do not address fully the diversity of disabilities that we have in our societies. The only way to address this is to ensure that persons with disability are involved in the deism and planning of the systems
default that are designed to protect the safety of the population in all countries.” 
defaultMargareta Wahlstrom, Special Rep
defaultresentative
default for UNISDR.
